<HEADLINE>
2007 TAICHUNG INTERNATIONAL TRAVEL FAIR ATTRACTING LARGE CROWDS
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei, April  23 (CNA) 04/27/07  19:12:43 (By Han Nai-kuo)
</P>
<P>
The 2007 Taichung International Travel Fair (TITF), being held at
the Taichung World Trade Center April 26- 29, has attracted tens
of thousands of visitors during the first two days of the
exhibition, organizers said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Fair visitors include large numbers of bargain hunters looking
for discount tour package deals offered by the 265 exhibitors
from Taiwan and abroad, according to officials from the Taichung
city government, which is holding the annual exhibition in
conjunction with the Tourism Bureau of the Ministry of
Transportation of Communications.
</P>
<P>
Exhibitors at the fair this year include the central government
and city and county governments from around Taiwan, as well as
foreign and domestic hotels, theme parks, travel agencies,
tourism organizations and travel magazines.
</P>
<P>
As one of the measures to attract crowds, the organizers have
been awarding the first 500 visitors to the show each day with
various gifts, including plane tickets, hotel vouchers, discount
coupons, health spa vouchers and various souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
Many tour operators at the exhibition are offering package deals
at markedly reduced prices, including a tour package of NT$1,999
(US$60) for three nights at any of the 89 hotels in Taiwan, China
and the Philippines which have joined the plan.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia, which has declared 2007 "Visit Malaysia Year" with the
goal to increase the number of tourist arrivals to 20 million
this year, is represented at the exhibition by the Malaysia
Tourism Promotion Board.
</P>
<P>
The board is offering three tour plans, each of five days, within
Malaysia, starting from NT$9,999.
</P>
<P>
As part of the fair's activities, the organizers have invited
troupes from Russia, Ukraine, France, Ghana and Malaysia to stage
various performances at the exhibition ground each day.
</P>
<P>
The Taichung International Travel Fair has become a major annual
event in central Taiwan since the fair was first held in 2000.
Last year's exhibition drew more than 70,000 visitors, up 12.5
percent over 2005, according to figures compiled the organizers.
</P>
